WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.676 --> 00:00:17.415
I am in search of another planet in the universe where life exists.
我正在宇宙中寻找另一颗有生命的行星。

2
00:00:18.246 --> 00:00:21.208
I can't see this planet with my naked eyes
靠肉眼肯定看不到，

3
00:00:21.232 --> 00:00:23.518
or even with the most powerful telescopes
即使借助如今最强大的望远镜

4
00:00:23.542 --> 00:00:24.892
we currently possess.
也看不到。

5
00:00:25.607 --> 00:00:27.671
But I know that it's there.
但我坚信它的存在。

6
00:00:27.695 --> 00:00:30.838
And understanding contradictions that occur in nature
了解自然界的矛盾法则，

7
00:00:30.862 --> 00:00:32.218
will help us find it.
能帮助我们找到它。

8
00:00:33.199 --> 00:00:34.350
On our planet,
在我们地球上，

9
00:00:34.374 --> 00:00:36.347
where there's water, there's life.
哪里有水，哪里就有生命。

10
00:00:36.712 --> 00:00:39.646
So we look for planets that orbit at just the right distance
因此我们将目光锁定在 那些与恒星的距离

11
00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:40.969
from their stars.
正合适的行星。

12
00:00:42.238 --> 00:00:43.389
At this distance,
这一距离，

13
00:00:43.413 --> 00:00:46.893
shown in blue on this diagram for stars of different temperatures,
在这张示意图中以蓝色表示， 根据恒星温度的高低而不同，

14
00:00:46.917 --> 00:00:50.771
planets could be warm enough for water to flow on their surfaces
能保证行星足够温暖, 使水保持液态，

15
00:00:50.795 --> 00:00:52.193
as lakes and oceans
形成湖泊和海洋，

16
00:00:52.217 --> 00:00:53.758
where life might reside.
就有可能孕育生命。

17
00:00:54.607 --> 00:00:58.321
Some astronomers focus their time and energy on finding planets
一些天文学家将时间和精力 投入到搜寻那些

18
00:00:58.345 --> 00:01:00.786
at these distances from their stars.
与其所围绕恒星的距离 在这一范围内的行星。

19
00:01:00.810 --> 00:01:03.213
What I do picks up where their job ends.
而我的工作紧随其后。

20
00:01:03.689 --> 00:01:06.673
I model the possible climates of exoplanets.
我建立这些系外行星的气候模型。

21
00:01:07.173 --> 00:01:08.999
And here's why that's important:
这项工作很重要：

22
00:01:09.023 --> 00:01:12.513
there are many factors besides distance from its star
因为要决定行星上是否有生命存在，

23
00:01:12.537 --> 00:01:15.141
that control whether a planet can support life.
除了与恒星的距离外， 还有许多其他因素。

24
00:01:16.117 --> 00:01:17.633
Take the planet Venus.
以金星为例。

25
00:01:18.466 --> 00:01:22.157
It's named after the Roman goddess of love and beauty,
它以罗马（神话中） 爱和美之女神的名字命名，

26
00:01:22.181 --> 00:01:25.791
because of its benign, ethereal appearance in the sky.
因为它看起来如此优雅而美丽。

27
00:01:26.307 --> 00:01:29.471
But spacecraft measurements revealed a different story.
然而宇宙飞船测量的结果 完全不是这么回事。

28
00:01:29.900 --> 00:01:33.869
The surface temperature is close to 900 degrees Fahrenheit,
金星表面的温度接近900华氏度，

29
00:01:33.893 --> 00:01:35.392
500 Celsius.
也就是500摄氏度。

30
00:01:35.971 --> 00:01:38.359
That's hot enough to melt lead.
这温度足以融化铅。

31
00:01:38.935 --> 00:01:42.773
Its thick atmosphere, not its distance from the sun, is the reason.
原因并不在于它与太阳的距离， 而在于它厚厚的大气层。

32
00:01:42.797 --> 00:01:45.900
It causes a greenhouse effect on steroids,
金星的大气层引发的温室效应，

33
00:01:45.924 --> 00:01:49.564
trapping heat from the sun and scorching the planet's surface.
将来自太阳的热量牢牢锁住， 将金星地表变成一片焦土。

34
00:01:50.001 --> 00:01:54.548
The reality totally contradicted initial perceptions of this planet.
这与我们之前对金星的想象 完全不一样。

35
00:01:55.548 --> 00:01:58.169
From these lessons from our own solar system,
我们太阳系的这个例子告诉我们，

36
00:01:58.193 --> 00:02:00.209
we've learned that a planet's atmosphere
行星的大气层

37
00:02:00.233 --> 00:02:03.835
is crucial to its climate and potential to host life.
对于其气候特点和 能否孕育生命至关重要。

38
00:02:04.787 --> 00:02:07.702
We don't know what the atmospheres of these planets are like
我们无法了解那些（可能孕育生命的） 行星的大气情况，

39
00:02:07.726 --> 00:02:12.094
because the planets are so small and dim compared to their stars
因为跟它们围绕的恒星相比， 它们又小又暗，

40
00:02:12.118 --> 00:02:13.783
and so far away from us.
而且离我们非常遥远。

41
00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:18.611
For example, one of the closest planets that could support surface water --
比如，离我们最近的， 可能有液态水存在的行星之一，

42
00:02:18.635 --> 00:02:21.992
it's called Gliese 667 Cc --
叫做“格利泽667Cc”——

43
00:02:22.016 --> 00:02:25.952
such a glamorous name, right, nice phone number for a name --
多美的名字啊，对吧， 做电话号码应该不错——

44
00:02:25.976 --> 00:02:28.411
it's 23 light years away.
离我们23光年。

45
00:02:28.911 --> 00:02:31.681
So that's more than 100 trillion miles.
也就是超过100万亿英里。

46
00:02:32.506 --> 00:02:34.819
Trying to measure the atmospheric composition
想要在一颗系外行星 从它的主恒星前经过时，

47
00:02:34.843 --> 00:02:38.859
of an exoplanet passing in front of its host star is hard.
测量它的大气成分太难了。

48
00:02:39.264 --> 00:02:41.144
It's like trying to see a fruit fly
就好比要看清一只

49
00:02:41.168 --> 00:02:43.454
passing in front of a car's headlight.
从车头灯前飞过的果蝇一样。

50
00:02:43.946 --> 00:02:47.645
OK, now imagine that car is 100 trillion miles away,
而且，这辆车还远在100万亿英里之外，

51
00:02:47.669 --> 00:02:51.041
and you want to know the precise color of that fly.
你还想看清这只果蝇的颜色。

52
00:02:52.438 --> 00:02:54.195
So I use computer models
因此我用计算机建模，

53
00:02:54.219 --> 00:02:57.322
to calculate the kind of atmosphere a planet would need
来计算一颗行星要形成 适宜水和生命存在的气候，

54
00:02:57.346 --> 00:03:00.045
to have a suitable climate for water and life.
需要何种大气类型。

55
00:03:01.259 --> 00:03:05.371
Here's an artist's concept of the planet Kepler-62f,
这是一张“开普勒62f”行星的概念图，

56
00:03:05.395 --> 00:03:06.878
with the Earth for reference.
旁边是用来做对比的地球。

57
00:03:07.327 --> 00:03:09.367
It's 1,200 light years away,
它距离我们1200光年，

58
00:03:09.391 --> 00:03:11.618
and just 40 percent larger than Earth.
体积只比地球大40%。

59
00:03:12.133 --> 00:03:16.181
Our NSF-funded work found that it could be warm enough for open water
我们的研究——由国家科学基金会资助—— 发现它温度适宜，可能存在液态水，

60
00:03:16.205 --> 00:03:20.314
from many types of atmospheres and orientations of its orbit.
它的大气拥有多种成分， 还有它的公转轨道（都可能证明这一点）。

61
00:03:20.338 --> 00:03:23.471
So I'd like future telescopes to follow up on this planet
因此我希望未来的望远镜 能继续观测这颗行星，

62
00:03:23.495 --> 00:03:25.066
to look for signs of life.
寻找生命存在的迹象。

63
00:03:26.296 --> 00:03:29.685
Ice on a planet's surface is also important for climate.
行星表面的冰层对于气候同样重要。

64
00:03:29.709 --> 00:03:32.904
Ice absorbs longer, redder wavelengths of light,
冰能吸收波长较长、更靠近红端的光，

65
00:03:32.928 --> 00:03:35.058
and reflects shorter, bluer light.
反射波长较短、更靠近蓝端的光。

66
00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:38.579
That's why the iceberg in this photo looks so blue.
这就是为什么这张照片里的 冰山看起来这么蓝。

67
00:03:38.912 --> 00:03:42.409
The redder light from the sun is absorbed on its way through the ice.
阳光里偏红的光在穿过冰层时被吸收。

68
00:03:42.433 --> 00:03:45.290
Only the blue light makes it all the way to the bottom.
只有蓝色的光一路走到底。

69
00:03:45.767 --> 00:03:48.159
Then it gets reflected back to up to our eyes
然后反射到我们的眼睛里，

70
00:03:48.183 --> 00:03:49.759
and we see blue ice.
我们就看到了蓝色的冰。

71
00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:53.384
My models show that planets orbiting cooler stars
我的模型显示，恒星温度越低， 其行星反而更温暖，

72
00:03:53.408 --> 00:03:56.576
could actually be warmer than planets orbiting hotter stars.
恒星温度越高， 其行星反而更寒冷。

73
00:03:56.600 --> 00:03:58.139
There's another contradiction --
这又是一个矛盾之处——

74
00:03:58.163 --> 00:04:01.937
that ice absorbs the longer wavelength light from cooler stars,
冰层吸收来自温度较低恒星 发出的波长较长的光，

75
00:04:01.961 --> 00:04:05.069
and that light, that energy, heats the ice.
而这些光，这些能量，又加热了冰层。

76
00:04:06.442 --> 00:04:08.802
Using climate models to explore
运用气候模型

77
00:04:08.826 --> 00:04:11.931
how these contradictions can affect planetary climate
来研究这些矛盾， 看它们如何影响行星的气候，

78
00:04:11.955 --> 00:04:15.129
is vital to the search for life elsewhere.
对于寻找地外生命至关重要。

79
00:04:15.948 --> 00:04:19.125
And it's no surprise that this is my specialty.
而我命中注定要从事这个行业。

80
00:04:19.535 --> 00:04:22.320
I'm an African-American female astronomer
我是一名非裔美籍女天文学家，

81
00:04:22.344 --> 00:04:24.456
and a classically trained actor
也是受过古典艺术训练的演员，

82
00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:28.315
who loves to wear makeup and read fashion magazines,
我喜欢化妆，喜欢时尚杂志，

83
00:04:28.339 --> 00:04:33.172
so I am uniquely positioned to appreciate contradictions in nature --
所以上帝派我来理解这些矛盾——

84
00:04:33.196 --> 00:04:34.308
(Laughter)
（笑声）

85
00:04:34.332 --> 00:04:37.796
(Applause)
（掌声）

86
00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:41.913
... and how they can inform our search for the next planet where life exists.
并利用它们来寻找 下一个有生命的行星。

87
00:04:42.465 --> 00:04:44.973
My organization, Rising Stargirls,
我成立的“新星女孩”组织，

88
00:04:44.997 --> 00:04:48.425
teaches astronomy to middle-school girls of color,
通过戏剧、写作和视觉艺术的方式，

89
00:04:48.449 --> 00:04:51.905
using theater, writing and visual art.
向非白人女中学生传授天文学知识。

90
00:04:52.517 --> 00:04:56.494
That's another contradiction -- science and art don't often go together,
这也是一对矛盾—— 科技和艺术看起来不同路，

91
00:04:56.518 --> 00:05:00.320
but interweaving them can help these girls bring their whole selves
但两者的交融可以 帮助这些姑娘们实现自我，

92
00:05:00.344 --> 00:05:01.543
to what they learn,
学有所成，

93
00:05:01.567 --> 00:05:05.007
and maybe one day join the ranks of astronomers
也许有一天她们也能成为 那些充满矛盾的

94
00:05:05.031 --> 00:05:06.785
who are full of contradictions,
天文学家中的一员，

95
00:05:06.809 --> 00:05:09.959
and use their backgrounds to discover, once and for all,
运用自身所学，彻底证明

96
00:05:09.983 --> 00:05:12.999
that we are truly not alone in the universe.
我们在茫茫宇宙中并不孤独。

97
00:05:14.253 --> 00:05:15.404
Thank you.
谢谢大家。

98
00:05:15.428 --> 00:05:24.244
(Applause)
（掌声）

